Put a large #saucepan{} of water on to boil for the noodles. Slice the @21 Day Aged British rump steaks{500%g} into strips as thinly as you can.

> TIP: Putting it in the freezer for a few minutes first will make this easier.

Remove the root from the @spring onion{3} and thinly slice (keep the green and white parts separate). Halve, then remove the core from the @green pepper{2} and slice into ½cm strips. Halve the @red chilli{½} lengthways, remove the seeds and finely chop. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} and @ginger{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a #small bowl{}, mix together the @ketchup{2%tbsp}, @soy sauce{3%tbsp}, @sweet chilli sauce{3%tbsp}, @rice vinegar{2%tbsp} and @water{4%tbsp}. Put the @Chinese five spice{2%tsp} and @cornflour{2%tsp} in a #mixing bowl{}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Add the steak and toss it in the cornflour mixture.

> TIP: Add less Chinese five spice if you want to keep things subtle!

Add the @egg noodle nests{3} to your pan of boiling water. Cook for ~{4%mins}. Drain in a #colander{} then refill your pan with cold water and submerge the noodles to stop them cooking further. Set aside until ready to serve.

Heat a good splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. Once almost smoking, carefully place the steak strips in the pan.

> TIP: You want the steak to get really crispy so don't crowd the pan. Cook it in batches if necessary.

Once each batch of steak is crispy around the edges, remove it to rest on some #kitchen paper{}.

Tip out any excess oil from the pan and add the pepper and chilli. Cook for ~{2%mins}. Add the garlic, ginger and the white parts of the spring onion. Cook for ~{1%minute} more. Add the sauce to the veggies in the pan. Cook until glossy, about ~{1%minute} more.

> TIP: Some like it hot but if that's not you, just use less chilli!

Drain the noodles again in the colander and add them to the pan along with the steak strips. Toss everything together and cook until piping hot, ~{2-3%mins}. Divide between your plates and serve with the green parts of the spring onion scattered over the top. Enjoy!